  "description": {
    "en": "Learn Docker fundamentals — images, containers, Dockerfiles, volumes, and how to containerize a Python application for consistent deployments.",
    "ta": "Docker அடிப்படைகளை கற்றுக்கொள்ளுங்கள் — images, containers, Dockerfiles, volumes, மற்றும் Python application-ஐ containerize செய்வது."
  },
  "xp_reward": 60,
  "story_variants": {
    "en": "## Vaathiyaar's Shipping Container\n\nVaathiyaar shows a picture of a cargo ship. \"Before shipping containers, every port loaded goods differently — chaos! Containers standardized everything. Docker does the same for software. Your app, its dependencies, its config — all packed in one container that runs the same everywhere.\"\n\n### What is Docker?\n- **Image** — A blueprint/recipe for your container (read-only)\n- **Container** — A running instance of an image (like an object from a class)\n- **Dockerfile** — Instructions to build an image\n- **Volume** — Persistent storage that survives container restarts\n- **Registry** — Storage for images (Docker Hub, GCR, ECR)\n\n### Why Docker?\n- \"Works on my machine\" → \"Works in the container\"\n- Same environment: dev, staging, production\n- Isolated: each container is its own little world\n- Reproducible: same Dockerfile = same result every time\n\n### Dockerfile Anatomy\n```dockerfile\nFROM python:3.12-slim\nWORKDIR /app\nCOPY requirements.txt .\nRUN pip install -r requirements.txt\nCOPY . .\nEXPOSE 8000\nCMD [\"python\", \"app.py\"]\n```\n\n> **Key Concept:** Docker containers are lightweight, portable, and reproducible. Build once, run anywhere — from your laptop to the cloud."
  },
